</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ab005"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<p>This study explores the grain refinement mechanisms of primary α-Al during solidification of Al-13 wt% Cu alloy modified by FeCoCrNiAl high-entropy alloy (HEA) particles via ultrasonic treatment. In situ X-ray radiography combined with machine learning-based computer vision techniques was employed to systematically analyze the nucleation and growth behaviors of α-Al grains. Results indicate a significant grain refinement effect associated with increased HEA particle content and higher cooling rates. Specifically, the addition of 2.0 wt% HEA particles reduce the primary α-Al grain size notably, achieving approximately 213 μm at a cooling rate of 1.0 K/s. At a cooling rate of 0.2 K/s, raising the HEA content from 0.5 to 2.0 wt% markedly increases the maximum nucleation rate (from 8.6 to 30.3 crystals/mm<sup>3</sup>/s), shortens the time required for grain growth cessation (from 18 s to 10 s). Similarly, at a fixed HEA content (1.0 wt%), increasing the cooling rate from 0.2 K/s to 1.0 K/s enhances the maximum nucleation rate (from 25.7 to 93.9 crystals/mm<sup>3</sup>/s) and reduces the grain growth cessation time (from 15 s to 9 s). Grain size distributions consistently exhibit normal distribution patterns. The addition of HEA particles significantly inhibits grain growth and reduces solute enrichment during solidification. These findings demonstrate that FeCoCrNiAl HEA particles facilitate grain refinement by effectively promoting heterogeneous nucleation and inhibiting grain growth.</p>
<section id="kg005" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Power ultrasound, Aluminum matrix composite, Ultrasonic treatment, High entropy alloy particles, X-ray radiography, Solidification</p></section></section><section id="s0005"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">1. Introduction</h2>
<p id="p0005">High mechanical performance, including strength and hardness, significantly contributes to extending the service life of engineered components and products. Grain refinement is among the most effective approaches for improving mechanical properties [<a href="#b0005" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0005">[1]</a>, <a href="#b0010" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0010">[2]</a>, <a href="#b0015" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0015">[3]</a>]. Advanced manufacturing techniques, such as incorporating foreign particles into metallic matrices and applying secondary treatments, have been developed to produce ultrafine grain structures [<a href="#b0020" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0020">4</a>]. These high-performance materials are especially sought after in industries such as aerospace, marine, military, and automotive, where material properties critically determine component reliability and longevity.</p>
<p id="p0010">Aluminum matrix composites (AMCs) have become increasingly preferred in these fields due to their distinct advantages over traditional materials, including reduced weight and improved resistance to corrosion and wear [<a href="#b0025" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0025">[5]</a>, <a href="#b0030" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0030">[6]</a>, <a href="#b0035" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0035">[7]</a>, <a href="#b0040" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0040">[8]</a>, <a href="#b0045" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0045">[9]</a>, <a href="#b0050" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0050">[10]</a>]. Previous studies has investigated various ceramic reinforcements to achieve grain refinement and improve mechanical performance [<a href="#b0055" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0055">[11]</a>, <a href="#b0060" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0060">[12]</a>, <a href="#b0065" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0065">[13]</a>]. For example, Li et al. [<a href="#b0070" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0070">14</a>] utilized TiB<sub>2</sub> nano-ceramic particles to refine aluminum alloys, reducing their microstructural sensitivity. Their study elucidated the mechanisms of microstructure evolution during solidification, thereby guiding the production of high-performance Al alloy cast billets. Seetharam et al. [<a href="#b0075" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0075">15</a>,<a href="#b0080" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0080">16</a>] investigated AMCs reinforced with B<sub>4</sub>C ceramic particles, analyzing strain behavior using mathematical modeling. Successfully introducing AlN-TiN/Al particles into pure aluminum led to notable enhancements in tensile strength, yield strength, and microhardness [<a href="#b0085" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0085">17</a>,<a href="#b0090" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0090">18</a>]. However, this modification also resulted in a reduction in elongation.</p>
<p id="p0015">However, despite their advantages, ceramic particles present several notable limitations. Specifically, ceramic reinforcements often negatively impact the plasticity and formability of materials, primarily attributable to the substantial disparities in their thermal expansion properties relative to metallic matrices [<a href="#b0095" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0095">19</a>]. Weak interfacial bonding at ceramic–metal interfaces frequently leads to crack initiation and subsequent failure, diminishing composite reliability. To overcome these shortcomings, HEAs—a new category of metallic alloys consisting of five or more main elements in almost equal molar proportions—have emerged as promising alternatives to traditional ceramic reinforcements [<a href="#b0100" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0100">20</a>]. Owing to these desirable attributes, HEA particles emerge as optimal reinforcement candidates for aluminum matrix composites. HEAs exhibit a range of superior qualities, such as elevated mechanical strength, thermal constancy, and resistance to abrasion [<a href="#b0105" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0105">21</a>,<a href="#b0110" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0110">22</a>]. Ultrasonic melt processing (USMP) and casting techniques enable uniform dispersion of HEA particles in an aluminum matrix, significantly enhancing grain refinement and mechanical properties while avoiding interfacial issues common with ceramic materials [<a href="#b0115" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0115">[23]</a>, <a href="#b0120" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0120">[24]</a>, <a href="#b0125" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0125">[25]</a>, <a href="#b0130" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0130">[26]</a>, <a href="#b0135" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0135">[27]</a>]. USMP enhances ingot integrity and quality through two primary mechanisms: cavitation-induced bubble collapse disrupts dendritic structures and intermetallic phases, while acoustic streaming promotes uniform solute distribution, leading to a more homogeneous spatial arrangement of microstructural features [<a href="#b0140" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0140">[28]</a>, <a href="#b0145" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0145">[29]</a>, <a href="#b0150" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0150">[30]</a>, <a href="#b0155" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0155">[31]</a>, <a href="#b0160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0160">[32]</a>]. Additionally, as metallic reinforcements, HEAs also offer improved compatibility with the aluminum matrix, leading to better bonding and more uniform microstructures [<a href="#b0165" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0165">33</a>,<a href="#b0170" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0170">34</a>].</p>
<p id="p0020">Recent studies have consistently shown that incorporating HEA particles into aluminum alloys can significantly refine the grain structure and enhance microstructural homogeneity. For instance, Pandey et al. [<a href="#b0175" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0175">35</a>] introduced Al<sub>4</sub>CrFeMnTi<sub>0</sub>.<sub>25</sub> HEA nanoparticles into Al-7150 via a dual-sonic sequential stir-casting method, achieving remarkable grain refinement (grain size reduced from 108.7 μm to 23.2 μm). Similarly, Luo et al. [<a href="#b0180" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0180">36</a>] observed grain refinement (124.4 μm to 38.2 μm) in AA1050 composites reinforced with Al<sub>0</sub>.<sub>5</sub>CoCrFeNi HEA particles using stir casting. Additionally, adding AlCoCrFeNiTi HEA particles has been shown to promote a transition in α-Al grain morphology from columnar to equiaxed, contributing to microstructural uniformity [<a href="#b0185" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0185">37</a>].</p>
<p id="p0025">These studies collectively corroborate that HEA particles are capable of markedly augmenting the mechanical performance of AMCs, especially through the mechanism of grain refinement [<a href="#b0190" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0190">[38]</a>, <a href="#b0195" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0195">[39]</a>, <a href="#b0200" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0200">[40]</a>]. While the microstructural benefits of HEA reinforcements have been widely documented, instantaneous observations of grain formation and development during the solidification process remain limited [<a href="#b0205" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0205">41</a>]. This lack of detailed mechanistic insight hinders the optimization strategies for AMC processing. To address this gap, in-situ solidification techniques have recently emerged as powerful tools for directly observing microstructural evolution during solidification [<a href="#b0210" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0210">[42]</a>, <a href="#b0215" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0215">[43]</a>, <a href="#b0220" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0220">[44]</a>, <a href="#b0225" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0225">[45]</a>]. In particular, in-situ X-ray imaging facilitates the immediate observation of grain nucleation and expansion, offering novel perspectives on the grain refinement process in AMCs mediated by HEA particles [<a href="#b0230" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0230">[46]</a>, <a href="#b0235" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0235">[47]</a>, <a href="#b0240" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0240">[48]</a>, <a href="#b0245" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0245">[49]</a>].</p>
<p id="p0030">In this study, Ultrasonic treatment was employed to achieve uniform dispersion of FeCoCrNiAl HEA particles within the Al-13 wt% Cu melt. Subsequently, the treated samples underwent in situ X-ray radiography to investigate the solidification process, capturing real-time insights into the nucleation and growth mechanisms of α-Al grains. we utilize in-situ X-ray imaging coupled with sophisticated artificial intelligence-driven image analysis methods to examine the influence of FeCoCrNiAl HEA particle reinforcements on grain initiation and development during the solidification of Al-13 wt% Cu alloys. Specifically, we examine the variations in grain morphology, nucleation events, grain-growth kinetics, and solute redistribution throughout solidification. By leveraging advanced image analysis algorithms, we precisely track individual grain nucleation and growth events, offering a comprehensive, quantitative understanding of how HEA particles refine microstructures during solidification.</p></section><section id="s0010"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">2. Materials and experimental methods</h2>
<section id="s0015"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.1. Sample Preparation</h3>
<p id="p0035">The raw materials consisted of high-purity aluminum (99.99 %), copper (99.9 %), and Equiatomic FeCoCrNiAl HEA particles. <a href="#f0005" class="usa-link">Fig. 1</a>(a) presents SEM images and elemental distribution of the FeCoCrNiAl particles. From the electron microscope image and EDS mapping, it is evident that the HEA particles exhibit a uniformly spherical morphology, with each element distributed evenly across the particles. In <a href="#f0005" class="usa-link">Fig. 1</a>(b), a detailed view of selected particles from the rectangular frame of <a href="#f0005" class="usa-link">Fig. 1</a>(a) is shown, clearly indicating that all components are present in nearly equal atomic ratios, with no noticeable segregation. The dimensional dispersion of the HEA particles was evaluated based on SEM imagery, with more than 300 particles assessed to guarantee precision. The dispersion closely adheres to a lognormal distribution. The data in <a href="#f0005" class="usa-link">Fig. 1</a>(c) highlight that the particle sizes are uniformly distributed in a logarithmic pattern, with dimensions spanning from 0.9 to 30.8 μm, and an average diameter of 10.1 μm. Additionally, the melting point of the HEA particles (∼1000 °C) greatly exceeds the processing temperatures used for ultrasonic melt treatment and solidification [<a href="#b0165" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0165">33</a>,<a href="#b0185" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0185">37</a>]. Thus, the HEA particles remain unmelted and thermally stable throughout the process (<a href="#f0010" class="usa-link">Fig. 2</a>). Although the particles are too fine to be distinctly visible in processed X-ray images like <a href="#f0025" class="usa-link">Fig. 5</a>, their presence is confirmed by SEM/EDS analysis and is reflected in the enhanced nucleation and grain refinement observed. Furthermore, these particles’ high thermal stability and low solubility in aluminum, along with their other favorable properties, underpin their effectiveness as grain refiners [<a href="#b0250" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0250">50</a>].</p>
