<p id="p0040">To fabricate the composite samples, high-purity aluminum and copper were initially loaded into an alumina crucible and melted in an inert argon environment within a resistance furnace. Once the mixture reached a molten state, it was maintained at 760 °C for a duration of 20 min. Thereafter, HEA particles that had been pre-conditioned (heated to 300 °C for a period of 2 h and enveloped in aluminum foil) were introduced into the molten alloy. Ultrasonic melt processing (frequency: 20 kHz, power: 1500 W) was then applied for 5 min to disperse the HEA particles uniformly within the melt, effectively breaking any particle agglomerations. A diagrammatic representation of the ultrasonic dispersion process is depicted in <a href="#f0015" class="usa-link">Fig. 3</a>(a). Following ultrasonic treatment, the molten material was poured into a conventional Reynolds golf T-mold.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0015"><h4 class="obj_head">Fig. 3.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr3.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/1301eb7a7346/gr3.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00015" height="246" width="664" alt="Fig. 3"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0015/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>(a) Diagram depicting the ultrasonic treatment process; (b) Schematic representation of the experimental setup for synchrotron X-ray radiography.</p></figcaption></figure><p id="p0045"><a href="#f0010" class="usa-link">Fig. 2</a> presents the SEM morphology and corresponding EDS elemental distribution of the HEA particle reinforced composite. In <a href="#f0010" class="usa-link">Fig. 2</a>(a) (secondary-electron mode), bright particles are visible within the Al matrix. EDS maps (<a href="#f0010" class="usa-link">Fig. 2</a>(b)–(f)) show these particles contain high concentrations of Cr, Fe, Co, and Ni (with a corresponding local depletion of Al), confirming they are the introduced AlCoCrFeNi HEA particles. The images demonstrate that the HEA particles are uniformly embedded in the Al matrix with no obvious agglomeration or debonding, thanks to the USMP treatment. In summary, the ultrasound-assisted dispersion yielded a consistent, well-integrated distribution of HEA particles throughout the matrix.</p>
<p id="p0050">Sheet-shaped specimens (approximately 15 × 10 × 1 mm) were excised from cylindrical samples via wire electrical discharge machining. The surfaces were subsequently polished and refined with sandpaper to achieve a final dimensional extent approximately 200 μm. This was succeeded by ultrasonic cleaning at anhydrous ethanol for a duration of 10 min. Anyone specimen interposed between two high-purity (99.6 %) Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> ceramic plates (20 mm × 15 mm × 0.1 mm) using a sealing mixture composed of silica sol and alumina particles.</p></section><section id="s0025"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.3. Radiography image acquisition and processing</h3>
<p id="p0055">In-situ X-ray radiography was performed at the BL13HB beamline of the Shanghai Synchrotron Radiation Facility (SSRF). To attain pronounced absorption contrast, monochromatic X-rays at 18 keV were produced via a dual-crystal monochromating device. The solidification dynamics were captured employing a scientific CMOS sensor integrated with an Optique Peter X-ray imaging system, as depicted in <a href="#f0015" class="usa-link">Fig. 3</a>(b).</p>
<p id="p0060">Prior to solidification testing, specimens were elevated to about 50 K above their liquidus temperature and dwelled for a period of 10 min to ensure melt equilibration. Solidification was thereafter conducted under quasi-isothermal circumstances at regulated cooling rates of 0.2, 0.5, and 1.0 K/s via a synchronized shutdown of both heaters, thereby preserving uniform thermal gradients. The region of interest (ROI) for imaging was consistently centered within each sample.</p>
<p id="p0065">Radiographic frames were acquired at 5 frames per second, providing a spatial field of view (FOV) of 3900 μm × 3900 μm and an effective pixel resolution of 3.25 μm following image processing. The overall analyzed volume was obtained by multiplying the projected scan area by the 200 μm thickness of the sample.</p></section><section id="s0030"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.4. Machine learning</h3>
<p id="p0070">The “You Only Look Once” version 8 (YOLOv8) deep learning algorithm was employed to analyze the grain nucleation and growth processes captured by in situ X-ray radiography. YOLOv8 is based on convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and enables efficient real-time object detection by concurrently performing classification, localization, and bounding box regression. The input image is divided into a grid of smaller cells, each responsible for identifying the presence of target objects. Through successive convolution and pooling operations, the network extracts increasingly abstract features, reducing spatial resolution while enhancing channel depth—from layer P1 to P5, as illustrated in <a href="#f0020" class="usa-link">Fig. 4</a>(a).</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0020"><h4 class="obj_head">Fig. 4.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr4.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/49c5888dedaa/gr4.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00020" height="601" width="789" alt="Fig. 4"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0020/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Computer vision algorithm principle based on YOLOv8.</p></figcaption></figure><p id="p0075">The output of YOLOv8 consists of predicted bounding box coordinates, object classes, and confidence scores for each detected object. To eliminate redundant overlapping predictions, a non-maximum suppression (NMS) algorithm is applied, retaining only the bounding box with the highest confidence score [<a href="#b0255" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0255">51</a>].</p>
<p id="p0080">Due to its robust performance, YOLOv8 has found broad application across multiple domains, including high-precision analysis of medical images (e.g., X-ray, CT, and MRI). Its effectiveness in grayscale image processing and single-object recognition makes it particularly well-suited for analyzing solidification image sequences. Consequently, YOLOv8 offers significant advantages for the automated and quantitative analysis of grain evolution in real-time radiographic imaging.</p>
<p id="p0085">In this study, YOLOv8 was utilized to quantitatively evaluate the formation and expansion of primary α-Al grains. As illustrated in <a href="#f0020" class="usa-link">Fig. 4</a>(d), the computer vision algorithm identifies each grain and assigns it a unique ID, which remains consistent throughout the grain’s entire growth process. Each identified grain is enclosed within a bounding box associated with its ID. The area of each grain in every frame is then approximated by calculating the area of the inscribed circle within its bounding box, and the resulting data are used for subsequent analysis. This Computer vision algorithm enables the automatic identification of grains in images such as <a href="#f0020" class="usa-link">Fig. 4</a>(b), with the detection results exemplified in <a href="#f0020" class="usa-link">Fig. 4</a>(c). A detailed visualization of the grain recognition process is provided in the <a href="#s0110" class="usa-link">Supplementary video</a> (<a href="#s0110" class="usa-link">Movie S2</a>).</p>
<p id="p0090"><a href="#f0025" class="usa-link">Fig. 5</a>(a) illustrates the temporal development of normalized grain density in Al-Cu alloys refined with FeCoCrNiAl HEA particles at cooling velocities of 0.2, 0.5, and 1.0 K/s. In these diagrams, time zero aligns with the emergence of the initial grain within the field of view (FOV), with each curve corresponding to a unique cooling velocity. Over 5000 individual grains were detected by the image recognition technique. As the cooling velocity increases, the grain density escalates more swiftly, while the normalized grain formation rate remains relatively invariant with respect to HEA particle composition under a consistent cooling condition. Within the restricted FOV, these curves effectively depict the temporal progression of the solid fraction and can be approximated using the Avrami equation [<a href="#b0255" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0255">51</a>]:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="e0005"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M1" display="block" altimg="si1.svg"><mrow><mtext>C</mtext><mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo linebreak="badbreak">-</mo><mi>exp</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mo linebreak="badbreak">-</mo><mi>K</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></math></td>
<td class="label">(1)</td>
</tr></table>
<p>where <em>C</em> represents the normalized density of the transformed phase (i.e., solid), <em>t</em> is time, and <em>K</em> and <em>n</em> are material-dependent constants. The fitted transformation curves at each cooling rate showed strong agreement with the data, and the best-fit <em>n</em> being 2.5, 2.6, and 2.6. These <em>n</em> values are indicative of a diffusion-controlled transformation in a quasi-three-dimensional system. Although more advanced formulations of the Avrami equation exist, our primary aim was to verify the correct operation of the computer vision algorithm.</p>
<p id="p0095"><a href="#f0025" class="usa-link">Fig. 5</a>(b)–(d) presents the radiographic images captured after solidification when the nucleation rate diminishes t<sub>0</sub> ≈ 0 for the three cooling rates. The captured images illustrate isotopically branched primary α-Al entities embedded within the matrix, a hallmark of structurally refined aluminum alloys. Quantitative assessment through manual counting within specified zones showed excellent concordance with grain density estimations obtained through advanced image-processing methodologies.</p></section></section><section id="s0035"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">3. Results</h2>
<section id="s0040"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.1. Effect of HEA contents</h3>
<section id="s0045"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.1.1. Effect of HEA content on nucleation</h4>
<p id="p0100"><a href="#f0030" class="usa-link">Fig. 6</a> delineates the image sequences of in situ X-radiography experiments of Al-13Cu alloys and their counterparts infused with incremental HEA particle additions (0.5, 1.0, and 2.0 wt%; all subsequent values are in weight percent), subjected to a fixed cooling rate of 0.2 K/s. The earliest frames (t = 0) denote the onset of visible nucleation within the captured observation area. After processing the images from <a href="#f0025" class="usa-link">Fig. 5</a>(b)–(d) using Eqs. <a href="#e0010" class="usa-link">(2)</a>, <a href="#e0015" class="usa-link">(3)</a>, we obtained the solute concentration distribution maps shown in <a href="#f0030" class="usa-link">Fig. 6</a>. Due to low X-ray absorption, grains with lower solute concentrations appear blue. As <a href="#f0030" class="usa-link">Fig. 6</a>(a) display, in absence of HEA particles, only three coarse grains were observed within the FOV, and the grain size exceeded 1 mm. <a href="#f0025" class="usa-link">Fig. 5</a>(b)–(d) shows the solidification sequence of Al-13Cu alloys at a 0.2 K/s cooling rate with various HEA particle contents (0.5, 1.0, and 2.0 wt%). The number of grains observed in the FOV is 173, 321, and 359 for HEA particle contents of 0.5, 1.0, and 2.0 wt%, respectively. The microstructural imagery reveals a pronounced elevation in grain density alongside a progressive diminution in individual grain scale as the loading fraction of HEA particulates increases. Specifically, grain counts within the observed FOV rose dramatically from 161 to 360 and further to 393 as the HEA addition increased from 0.5 to 1.0 and then to 2.0 wt%. These findings confirm that HEA inclusions serve as efficient nucleation catalysts, significantly intensifying grain refinement. As their concentration rises, the initial α-Al structures exhibit a progressive shift toward a compact, spheroidized equiaxed configuration. The red circular region in <a href="#f0030" class="usa-link">Fig. 6</a>(d) indicates a gas bubble formed during solidification, which causes a local data anomaly—an unavoidable issue in synchrotron radiography [<a href="#b0260" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0260">52</a>]. To minimize the impact of such bubbles on the solute concentration analysis, the affected regions were cropped out using MATLAB’s imcrop function [<a href="#b0220" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0220">44</a>]. A top-to-bottom temperature gradient exists during solidification due to the equipment reasons. However, since all experiments were conducted under the same controlled cooling rate and thermal boundary conditions, this inherent temperature gradient was consistent across all sample groups and treated as a constant background factor.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0030"><h5 class="obj_head">Fig. 6.</h5>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr6.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/a93ed168a876/gr6.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00030" height="662" width="689" alt="Fig. 6"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0030/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Solidification sequence of Al-13Cu alloy with various HEA particle contents at a cooling rate of 0.2 K/s: (a) 0 %, (b) 0.5 wt%, (c) 1.0 wt%, (d) 2.0 wt%.</p></figcaption></figure><p id="p0105"><a href="#f0035" class="usa-link">Fig. 7</a> quantitatively illustrates the changes in grain number density and nucleation rate during solidification at different HEA contents, using synchrotron radiographs and a computer vision algorithm. Specifically, the grain number density and nucleation rate during the solidification process under varying HEA contents are calculated by tracking changes in the IDs across each frame. It is clear that the spatial distribution of HEA particulates within the observation region markedly impacts nucleation density. Under a controlled cooling rate of 0.2 K/s, the alloy containing 2.0 wt% HEA particles produced 321 grains, a striking contrast to the mere 3 grains observed in the unmodified Al-13Cu alloy, representing an approximate 107-fold increase. As displayed in <a href="#f0035" class="usa-link">Fig. 7</a>(a), the number of grains in the solidification sequence with different HEA contents increases rapidly in the first 20 s and then tends to be stable. Additionally, increasing HEA particle content from 0.5 to 2.0 wt% enhanced the maximum nucleation rate from 8.6 to 30.3 crystals/mm<sup>3</sup>/s and increased the maximum grain density from 62.9 to 152.4 crystals/mm<sup>3</sup>, highlighting the effectiveness of HEA particles in promoting nucleation.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0035"><h5 class="obj_head">Fig. 7.</h5>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr7.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/8d4c0a50a4aa/gr7.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00035" height="248" width="664" alt="Fig. 7"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0035/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>(a) The grain number density with different amounts of grain refiner added, 0.5, 1.0, and 2.0 wt% at a cooling rate of 0.2 K/s; (b) nucleation rate with respect to solidification time.</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id="s0050"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.1.2. Effect of HEA content on growth</h4>
<p id="p0110">To further investigate the influence of HEA particle additions on grain growth kinetics, solidification sequence data were processed using computer vision algorithms. The area change of each grain is tracked via its identification box across frames, and the final bounding box size is used to approximate the grain size. The inscribed circle of the bounding box represents the area of the labeled grain. For each HEA concentration, over 125 representative grains from different stages of solidification were selected and analyzed. <a href="#f0040" class="usa-link">Fig. 8</a>(a)–(c) present the dynamic variation in grain size over the course of growth, with color mapping used to indicate the chronological sequence of nucleation.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0040"><h5 class="obj_head">Fig. 8.</h5>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr8.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/90e070b1e512/gr8.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00040" height="389" width="788" alt="Fig. 8"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0040/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Changes of grain area with time when cooling rate is 0.2 K/s at different HEA particle additions (a) 0.5 wt%, (b) 1.0 wt%, and (c) 2.0 wt%; Distribution of diameter in with time when cooling rate is 0.5 K/s at different HEA particle additions (d) 0.5 wt%, (e) 1.0 wt%, and (f) 2.0 wt%.</p></figcaption></figure><p id="p0115">In each sequence, grains that nucleate earlier tend to grow for longer durations and achieve larger final sizes, as they experience less spatial competition. Conversely, grains that nucleate later are constrained by surrounding grains, resulting in shorter growth periods and smaller final sizes. This spatial interaction reflects classic impingement effects in grain growth.</p>
<p id="p0120">The data reveal that augmenting the HEA particle content contributes not only to a diminution in average grain scale but also to a more rapid arrest of grain coarsening dynamics. Specifically, the average time required for grains to reach their maximum size decreases significantly—from approximately 18 s at 0.5 wt% HEA to about 10 s at 2.0 wt%. Furthermore, the grain area evolution curves become progressively smoother and more consistent with higher HEA content, indicating a more uniform and stable growth environment facilitated by enhanced nucleation efficiency and spatial saturation. Quantitative assessment of final grain size distributions (<a href="#f0040" class="usa-link">Fig. 8</a>(d)–(f)) reinforces this trend, revealing systematic refinement with successive increments in HEA particle dosage. Average grain size reduced from 320 μm (0.5 wt%) to 253 μm (1.0 wt%) and ultimately to 244 μm (2.0 wt%).</p></section></section><section id="s0055"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.2. Effect of cooling rates</h3>
<section id="s0060"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.2.1. Effect of cooling rates on nucleation</h4>
<p id="p0125"><a href="#f0045" class="usa-link">Fig. 9</a>(a)–(c) showcase sequential in-situ X-ray radiographic observations of Al-13Cu systems alloyed by 1.0 wt% HEA particulates, subjected to varying thermal extraction rates (0.2, 0.5, and 1.0 K/s). The series distinctly illustrates how different cooling intensities govern microstructural evolution, particularly influencing the onset and propagation of grain formation. An increase in the imposed cooling gradient led to a rise in grain density within the observed region—from 359 at 0.2 K/s to 468 at 0.5 K/s, reaching 522 at 1.0 K/s—underscoring the strong nucleation-promoting effect of higher solidification rates.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0045"><h5 class="obj_head">Fig. 9.</h5>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr9.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/5858011f6977/gr9.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00045" height="499" width="690" alt="Fig. 9"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0045/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Solidification sequence of Al-13Cu alloy refined with 1.0 wt% HEA particles at varying cooling rates: (a) 0.2 K/s; (b) 0.5 K/s; (c) 1.0 K/s.</p></figcaption></figure><p id="p0130">Quantitative analysis from synchrotron X-ray imaging, shown in <a href="#f0050" class="usa-link">Fig. 10</a>, confirms this trend. Maintaining an HEA loading of 1.0 wt%, elevating the solidification rate within the range of 0.2 to 1.0 K/s substantially boosted the peak nucleation frequency (from 25.7 to 93.9 crystals/mm<sup>3</sup>/s) and enhanced the ultimate grain number density (from 140.3 to 209.3 crystals/mm<sup>3</sup>). Moreover, the time required for nucleation of the final grain was significantly reduced from approximately 27 s at 0.2 K/s to just 8 s at 1.0 K/s. These results highlight the critical role of cooling rate in accelerating grain nucleation and growth kinetics, thus refining microstructure effectively.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0050"><h5 class="obj_head">Fig. 10.</h5>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr10.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/8d4800b11c64/gr10.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00050" height="262" width="662" alt="Fig. 10"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0050/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>(a) The grain number density with 1.0 wt% HEA added at cooling rate of 0.2, 0.5, 1.0 K/s; (b) Nucleation rate in relation to solidification time.</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id="s0065"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.2.2. Effect of cooling rates on growth</h4>
<p id="p0135">Further insights into grain growth dynamics at different cooling rates were obtained using computer vision analyses of selected grains. Over 125 representative grains at each cooling rate were systematically analyzed, as depicted in <a href="#f0055" class="usa-link">Fig. 11</a>(a)–(c). With increasing cooling rates, grains exhibited reduced average sizes and faster growth termination times. As an illustration, grain growth terminated near 15 s at a thermal gradient of 0.2 K/s, but this duration was significantly reduced to about 9 s under a cooling intensity of 1.0 K/s. Additionally, smoother growth trajectories at higher cooling rates indicated more uniform and stable grain growth processes.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0055"><h5 class="obj_head">Fig. 11.</h5>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr11.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/5f23449b6f76/gr11.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00055" height="386" width="788" alt="Fig. 11"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0055/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Changes of grain area with time refined by 1.0 wt% HEA particles at different cooling rates (a) 0.2; (b) 0.5; (c) 1.0 K/s; Distribution of diameter in with time refined by 1.0 wt% HEA particles at different cooling rates (d) 0.2 K/s; (e) 0.5 K/s; (f) 1.0 K/s.</p></figcaption></figure><p id="p0140">Finally, statistical evaluation of grain size distributions (<a href="#f0055" class="usa-link">Fig. 11</a>(d)–(f)) confirmed the progressive grain refinement with an increasing cooling rate. Specifically, the average grain size declined from 248 μm (0.2 K/s), to 221 μm (0.5 K/s), and ultimately to 217 μm at 1.0 K/s. These measurements demonstrate a consistent and clear trend, further reinforcing the conclusion that increased cooling rate effectively enhances grain refinement in HEA-reinforced Al-Cu alloys.</p></section></section><section id="s0070"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.3. Final grain size</h3>
<p id="p0145">The observed grain counts within the FOV are strongly influenced by both HEA particle content and cooling rate. For instance, under a fixed HEA incorporation of 0.5 wt%, the grain count increases from 161 to 210 as the thermal extraction rate intensifies from 0.2 to 1.0 K/s. Conversely, elevating the HEA concentration to 2.0 wt% yields a substantial rise in grain population—reaching 393, 499, and 587 at thermal gradients of 0.2, 0.5, and 1.0 K/s. The corresponds to more than a 2.5-fold enhancement relative to the lower additive level. The mean grain diameter, <em>d</em>, can approximate using the following expression [<a href="#b0265" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0265">53</a>]:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="e0010"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M2" display="block" altimg="si2.svg"><mrow><mi>d</mi><mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>6</mtext><msub><mi>S</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">FOV</mi></mrow></msub><mi>δ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>π</mi><mi>N</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mtext>1/3</mtext></msup></mrow></math></td>
<td class="label">(2)</td>
</tr></table>
<p>where <em>S<sub>FOV</sub></em> represents the FOV area, <em>δ</em> is the alloy foil thickness, and <em>N</em> is grain count. Grain size, as consolidated in <a href="#f0060" class="usa-link">Fig. 12</a>, reveal pronounced refinement driven by both elevated HEA loading and intensified thermal extraction. Specifically, with a 1.0 wt% HEA addition under a cooling intensity of 1.0 K/s, the grain size is reduced to roughly 213  µm. Considering industrial conditions typically involve higher cooling rates (&gt;1.0 K/s), HEA additions are highly promising for achieving practical grain sizes below 200 µm.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0060"><h4 class="obj_head">Fig. 12.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr12.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/867e4a6f2f31/gr12.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00060" height="555" width="679" alt="Fig. 12"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0060/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Average grain size of Al-13Cu alloy refined with HEA particles at various cooling rates.</p></figcaption></figure></section></section><section id="s0075"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">4. Discussion</h2>
<section id="s0080"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.1. Effect of HEA particles on grain growth</h3>
<p id="p0150">The addition of HEA particles significantly inhibits grain growth during solidification. As clearly shown in <a href="#f0065" class="usa-link">Fig. 13</a>(a), increasing the HEA particle content markedly reduces the grain growth rate. An inset binary mask highlights grain morphologies for different HEA additions, and the statistical analysis of these areas provides the data for <a href="#f0065" class="usa-link">Fig. 13</a>(a). The images demonstrate that as HEA content increases, grain shapes become progressively more spherical and uniform.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0065"><h4 class="obj_head">Fig. 13.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr13.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/66fa1086c446/gr13.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00065" height="416" width="788" alt="Fig. 13"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0065/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>(a) Grain area in the early nucleation stage at a cooling rate of 0.2 K/s; (b) The relationship between the area growth rate of all grains and time during the solidification process; The binary mask to distinguish different HEA particle additions (c) 0, (d) 0.5, (e) 1.0, (f) 2.0 wt%.</p></figcaption></figure><p id="p0155">Quantitatively, at 4 s after nucleation, the average grain area in the alloy without HEA particles is approximately 46 × 10<sup>3</sup> µm<sup>2</sup>. Incorporating HEA particulates at concentrations of 0.5, 1.0, and 2.0 wt% results in a sharp decline in typical grain area, decreasing to 10.8 × 10<sup>3</sup> µm<sup>2</sup>, 4.2 × 10<sup>3</sup> µm<sup>2</sup>, and 3.1 × 10<sup>3</sup> µm<sup>2</sup>, accordingly. Thus, the average grain area is diminished by nearly 15-fold as the HEA concentration escalates from zero to 2.0 wt%, underscoring the pronounced grain-growth retardation effect imparted by HEA particles.</p>
<p id="p0160"><a href="#f0065" class="usa-link">Fig. 13</a>(b) shows the evolution of total grain area over time for various HEA loadings, based on the frame-by-frame area measurements of all grains. Maintaining a steady cooling gradient of 0.2 K/s, the apex rate of grain expansion sharply declines from 100.8 × 10<sup>3</sup> µm<sup>2</sup>/s at zero HEA content to only 1.12 × 10<sup>3</sup> µm<sup>2</sup>/s at 2.0 wt% HEA. These results clearly confirm that incorporating HEA particles effectively suppresses grain growth, playing a key role in achieving refined grain structures. Furthermore, due to the confined dimensions of the observation window, when the unrefined aluminum alloy solidifies, oversized grains partially protruding beyond the FOV margins are omitted from the statistical evaluation. Consequently, derived grain growth velocity underestimates actual value, although it still maintains a degree of reliability.</p>
<p id="p0165"><a href="#f0065" class="usa-link">Fig. 13</a>(c)–(f) presents the binary masks of grains grown at 4th second under the 0.2 K/s cooling rate for different HEA particle additions. Note that the cropped area sizes were adjusted for measurement convenience: 210 × 210 pixels in <a href="#f0065" class="usa-link">Fig. 13</a>(c), and 100 × 100 pixels in <a href="#f0065" class="usa-link">Fig. 13</a>(d), (e), and (f).</p></section><section id="s0085"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.2. Effect of HEA particles on solute enrichment</h3>
<p id="p0170">We quantitatively analyzed the changes in solute concentrations to assess the impact of HEA particles on solute enrichment during solidification. The initial liquid radiograph prior to nucleation is selected as a reference frame, representing average intensity <em>I</em><sub>0</sub> corresponding to the nominal solute concentration C<sub>0</sub> (13 wt% Cu). Assuming uniform sample thickness, the solute concentration difference (<em>ΔC</em>) at pixel coordinates (<em>x, y</em>) relative to the reference intensity <em>I<sub>0</sub></em> of the overall liquid phase is ascertainable through the subsequent formula [<a href="#b0270" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0270">54</a>]:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="e0015"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M3" display="block" altimg="si3.svg"><mrow><msub><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub><mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>δ</mi></mfrac><mi>ln</mi><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>I</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">Al</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mi>ρ</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">Al</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>-</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">Cu</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mi>ρ</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">Cu</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac></mrow></math></td>
<td class="label">(3)</td>
</tr></table>
<p>where <em>I</em><sub>0</sub> denotes the incident beam intensity, <em>I</em> the transmitted intensity, <em>μ<sub>Al</sub></em> and <em>μ<sub>Cu</sub></em> the mass absorption coefficients of aluminum and copper, respectively, while ρ<sub>Cu</sub> and ρ<sub>Al</sub> represent their densities. The solute concentration (<em>C</em>(<em>x,y</em>)) at pixel (<em>x,y</em>) is given by:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="e0020"><tr>
<td class="formula"><math id="M4" display="block" altimg="si4.svg"><mrow><mi>C</mi><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>∗</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></td>
<td class="label">(4)</td>
</tr></table>
<p id="p0175">By applying Eqs. <a href="#e0015" class="usa-link">(3)</a>, <a href="#e0020" class="usa-link">(4)</a> to the original dataset (e.g., <a href="#s0110" class="usa-link">Movie S1</a>), the local Cu solute concentration in each frame can be extracted. Throughout the solidification process, the equilibrium partition coefficient for the Al-Cu alloy, being less than one, induces continuous solute atom segregation at the migrating solid–liquid interface. This phenomenon causes substantial solute enrichment and steep concentration differentials, which amplify chemical segregation and detrimentally affect the mechanical integrity of the alloy.</p>
<p id="p0180"><a href="#f0070" class="usa-link">Fig. 14</a>(a)–(d) shows solute concentration maps captured at the 18th second from different sequences, clearly illustrating solute enrichment at the solid–liquid interfaces. The circular regions marked in <a href="#f0070" class="usa-link">Fig. 14</a>(a) and (d) correspond to bubbles formed within the FOV during the solidification process, leading to anomalous data in their vicinity. To mitigate the impact of these bubbles, the affected areas were cropped using the imcrop function in MATLAB during the calculation of solute concentration [<a href="#b0270" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0270">54</a>]. In unrefined alloy (<a href="#f0070" class="usa-link">Fig. 14</a>(a)), larger grains and prolonged growth durations result in severe solute rejection, creating regions of high solute concentration. However, with increasing HEA particle additions, solute concentration maps progressively shift toward blue tones (<a href="#f0070" class="usa-link">Fig. 14</a>(b)–(d)), indicating substantially diminished solute expulsion due to the refined, smaller grain sizes and shorter growth durations.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0070"><h4 class="obj_head">Fig. 14.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr14.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/8d71b16ba749/gr14.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00070" height="401" width="788" alt="Fig. 14"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0070/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Solute concentration mapping under conditions of 0.2 K/s cooling rate and varying HEA particle additions: (a) 0, (b) 0.5, (c) 1.0, (d) 2.0 wt%; (e) Maximum solute concentration in the mapping refined by HEA particles.</p></figcaption></figure><p id="p0185"><a href="#f0070" class="usa-link">Fig. 14</a>(e) quantitatively compares the temporal evolution of the maximum solute concentration in the melt across solidification sequences with varying HEA particle additions. The maximum solute concentration continuously rises as solidification progresses. Notably, after nucleation ceases— approximately at 16 s, 18 s, and 23 s for HEA contents of 0.5, 1.0, and 2.0 wt% (<a href="#f0035" class="usa-link">Fig. 7</a>)—a rapid increase in solute concentration occurs. Specifically, under the 0.2 K/s cooling rate and after 30 s, the peak solute concentration significantly decreases from 19.7 wt% Cu (without HEA) to 14.6 wt% Cu (2.0 wt% HEA). These results clearly demonstrate that HEA particle additions effectively mitigate solute enrichment during grain growth, contributing significantly to microstructural refinement in Al-Cu alloys.</p></section><section id="s0090"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.3. Grain refinement mechanism of HEA particles</h3>
<p id="p0190">Integrating FeCoCrNiAl HEA particles through ultrasonic treatment into an Al-Cu melt refines the microstructure through two complementary actions: heterogeneous nucleation and growth inhibition. As reported by Yang et al. [<a href="#b0165" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0165">33</a>,<a href="#b0275" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0275">55</a>], a diffusion layer, ∼200 nm thick, forms at the Al/HEA interface during ultrasonic dispersion. High-resolution TEM combined with SAED shows that this layer consists mainly of an Fe-Ni phase with a face-centered-cubic (FCC) lattice that matches the α-Al matrix. This interfacial layer also suppresses detrimental interfacial reactions while maintaining strong metallurgical bonding, allowing effective load transfer and further stabilising the newly formed grains. Furthermore, the application of USMP facilitates the uniform dispersion of HEA particles throughout the melt, allowing a greater number of particles to act as nucleation substrates and thereby significantly enhancing grain refinement [<a href="#b0280" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0280">[56]</a>, <a href="#b0285" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0285">[57]</a>, <a href="#b0290" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0290">[58]</a>]. Our in-situ observations reveal that introducing HEA particles via ultrasonic treatment decreases solute buildup in the liquid and fosters a more homogeneous solute distribution among dendrites (<a href="#f0070" class="usa-link">Fig. 14</a>), while also enhancing the nucleation rate and increasing grain count (<a href="#f0035" class="usa-link">Fig. 7</a>). Consequently, the promotion of nucleation by HEA particles effectively reduces the grain size.</p>
<p id="p0195">Not every particle in the melt becomes a nucleation site. Extensive studies have shown that second-phase particles, including HEA nanoparticles, can impede grain boundary migration through mechanisms such as Zener pinning, solute drag, and interfacial energy modification. HEA particles that remain in the liquid (illustrated as Sphere 2 in <a href="#f0075" class="usa-link">Fig. 15</a>) obstruct the advancing solid–liquid interface and hinder grain-boundary migration [<a href="#b0295" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b0295">59</a>]. Their high hardness and low solubility create a physical barrier that shortens the duration of dendritic growth and encourages the formation of finer, more equiaxed grains. <a href="#f0075" class="usa-link">Fig. 15</a> schematically summarizes these dual roles: particles that act as nucleation sites (Sphere 1) increase the number of grains, while non-nucleating particles (Sphere 2) limit the subsequent growth of grains. Together, an increase in nucleation site density coupled with a decrease in growth kinetics leads to significantly refined and more equiaxed grain structures. This dual action explains the pronounced grain size reduction and morphological transition from dendritic to equiaxed observed as HEA content rises.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f0075"><h4 class="obj_head">Fig. 15.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12423412_gr15.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/d294/12423412/a130a8d89e0f/gr15.jpg" loading="lazy" id="lk00075" height="267" width="708" alt="Fig. 15"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f0075/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Schematic illustrating how HEA clusters affect grain growth.</p></figcaption></figure></section></section><section id="s0095"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">5. Conclusions</h2>
<p id="p0200">In-situ synchrotron X-ray radiography, plus quantitative image analysis, clarifies how FeCoCrNiAl HEA particles through ultrasonic treatment refine the microstructure of Al-Cu alloys. The principal findings are:</p>
<ul id="l0005" class="list" style="list-style-type:none">
<li id="o0005"><p id="p0205">Ultrasonic dispersion of HEA particles markedly refines primary α-Al grains. As the HEA particles content increase from 0.5 % to 2.0 %, At 0.2 K/s, the grain density increases from 62.9 to 152.4 crystals/mm<sup>3</sup> and the average grain size falls from 328 µm to 243 µm. This is because the HEA particles provide heterogeneous nucleation sites during solidification, thereby reducing the size of grains.</p></li>
<li id="o0010"><p id="p0210">In each sequence, grains that nucleate earlier tend to grow for longer durations and achieve larger final sizes, as they experience less spatial competition. Conversely, grains that nucleate later are constrained by surrounding grains, resulting in shorter growth periods and smaller final sizes. With a fixed cooling rate of 0.2 K/s, raising the HEA content advances the time at which grain growth halts—from ≈18 s (0.5 wt%) to ≈10 s (2.0 wt%). At a constant 1.0 wt% HEA, increasing the cooling rate shortens the growth-cessation time from ≈15 s (0.2 K/s) to ≈9 s (1.0 K/s) and yields finer grains.</p></li>
<li id="o0015"><p id="p0215">The addition of HEA particles significantly inhibits grain growth and reduces solute enrichment during solidification. At 0.2 K s<sup>−1</sup>, the maximum grain-area growth rate declines from 100.8 × 10<sup>3</sup> µm<sup>2</sup>/s (no HEA) to 1.12 × 10<sup>3</sup> µm<sup>2</sup>/s (2.0 wt% HEA), while grain morphology shifts from dendritic to equiaxed. Simultaneously, the peak Cu concentration in the residual liquid drops from 19.7 wt% (no HEA) to 13.8 wt% (2.0 wt% HEA). This indicates that most of the HEA particles adhere to the solid–liquid interface, which reduces the grain growth rate.</p></li>
</ul>
<p id="p0220">FeCoCrNiAl particles refine α-Al grains by (i) providing potent heterogeneous-nucleation substrates that raise the nucleation rate and (ii) lowering interfacial solute buildup, which curtails subsequent grain growth. These dual effects—nucleation promotion and growth suppression—should extend to other HEA/Al systems, offering a strategy for microstructural control in Al-based alloys.</p></section><section id="s0100"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">CRediT authorship contribution statement</h2>
